{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"539ad04d-7d67-45db-b57f-119d51e226f3","content":"Here's what to change:\n\n1. **Update your `.csproj`** — add/replace these packages:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Remove or keep NUnit3TestAdapter, but add: -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"NUnit\" Version=\"4.*\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"NUnit3TestAdapter\" Version=\"4.6.0\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.NUnit\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n\n<!-- Enable the new platform: -->\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n2. **Add an entry point** — create or update your `Program.cs` (or set `<GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>true</GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>` in `<PropertyGroup>` to auto-generate it).\n\n3. **Run tests** with:\n   ```\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   or directly:\n   ```\n   dotnet run -- --help   # to see new CLI options\n   ```\n\n**Key differences to be aware of:**\n- `.runsettings` files are **not** used; configure via CLI args or code instead.\n- Test output and flags change (e.g., `--filter` becomes `--treenode-filter`).\n- Each test project becomes its own executable.\n\nNo changes to your actual `[Test]` / `[TestFixture]` code are needed — the NUnit APIs remain the same.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1fc3efc6-c55a-4816-b879-edd53a102984","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating an NUnit test project from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. This is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about the migration steps.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"043F:12A859:1E3BA9A:2205300:69E8194F"},"id":"7475cb13-7a88-4e92-83a1-f824906b919a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:42:11.411Z","parentId":"209abde8-8d2f-4e95-9157-c3ef0de4456b"}
